**Write a C++ Function to Convert Markdown to HTML**

### Problem Statement

Write a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing html formatted text.

### Solution

#### Approach

1. **Parse the Markdown**: Use a markdown parser library to convert the markdown text into a structured representation.
2. **Generate HTML**: Use the structured representation to generate HTML.

#### Implementation

**Step 1: Include Necessary Libraries**

- `pugixml`: A lightweight XML parser for C++.
- `doctest`: A C++11 unit testing framework.

**Step 2: Define the Function**

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <iostream>
#include "pugixml.hpp"
#include "doctest.h"

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Parse the markdown
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load_string(markdown.c_str());

    // Generate HTML
    std::string html;
    html += "<html>\n";
    html += "<head>\n";
    html += "<title>Markdown to HTML</title>\n";
    html += "</head>\n";
    html += "<body>\n";

    // Iterate through the nodes and generate HTML
    for (pugi::xml_node node : doc.child("document").children()) {
        if (node.type() == pugi::node_element) {
            std::string tag = node.name();
            std::string content = node.text().as_string();

            if (tag == "p") {
                html += "<p>" + content + "</p>\n";
            } else if (tag == "h1") {
                html += "<h1>" + content + "</h1>\n";
            } else if (tag == "h2") {
                html += "<h2>" + content + "</h2>\n";
            } else if (tag == "h3") {
                html += "<h3>" + content + "</h3>\n";
            } else if (tag == "h4") {
                html += "<h4>" + content + "</h4>\n";
            } else if (tag == "h5") {
                html += "<h5>" + content + "</h5>\n";
            } else if (tag == "h6") {
                html += "<h6>" + content + "</h6>\n";
            } else if (tag == "ul") {
                html += "<ul>\n";
                for (pugi::xml_node child : node.children()) {
                    if (child.type() == pugi::node_element && child.name() == "li") {
                        html += "<li>" + child.text().as_string() + "</li>\n";
                    }
                }
                html += "</ul>\n";
            } else if (tag == "ol") {
                html += "<ol>\n";
                int i = 1;
                for (pugi::xml_node child : node.children()) {
                    if (child.type() == pugi::node_element && child.name() == "li") {
                        html += "<li>" + std::to_string(i) + ". " + child.text().as_string() + "</li>\n";
                        i++;
                    }
                }
                html += "</ol>\n";
            } else if (tag == "a") {
                html += "<a href=\"" + node.attribute("href").value() + "\">" + content + "</a>\n";
            } else if (tag == "img") {
                html += "<img src=\"" + node.attribute("src").value() + "\" alt=\"" + content + "\">\n";
            }
        }
    }

    html += "</body>\n";
    html += "</html>\n";

    return html;
}
```

**Step 3: Test the Function**

```cpp
TEST_CASE("Convert Markdown to HTML") {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n\nThis is a **bold** and *italic* text.\n\n- Item 1\n- Item 2\n\n1. Item 1\n2. Item 2\n\n[Link](https://example.com)\n\n![Image](https://example.com/image.png)";
    std::string expected_html = "<html>\n<head>\n<title>Markdown to HTML</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n<h1>Hello, World!</h1>\n<p>This is a <strong>bold</strong> and <em>italic</em> text.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Item 1</li>\n<li>Item 2</li>\n</ul>\n<ol>\n<li>Item 1</li>\n<li>Item 2</li>\n</ol>\n<a href=\"https://example.com\">Link</a>\n<img src=\"https://example.com/image.png\" alt=\"Image\">\n</body>\n</html>\n";
    CHECK(convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown) == expected_html);
}
```

### Conclusion

This solution uses the `pugixml` library to parse the markdown text and generate a structured representation. Then, it uses this representation to generate HTML. The function is tested using the `doctest` framework.

