**Question**: How do I compare strings in Java?

**Answer**: To compare strings in Java, use the `.equals()` method instead of the `==` operator.

**Explanation**:
- The `==` operator checks if two objects are the same instance.
- The `.equals()` method checks if the content of two strings is the same.

**Example**:
```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

// This will return false
if (str1 == str2) {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same instance.");
} else {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 are not the same instance.");
}

// This will return true
if (str1.equals(str2)) {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 have the same content.");
} else {
  System.out.println("str1 and str2 do not have the same content.");
}
```

**Conclusion**:
- Use `.equals()` to compare the content of two strings.
- Use `==` to compare if two objects are the same instance.

